Heh Zozz, this was an amusing sentence.  Quantum theory throws somewhat of a wrench into the old notion that an atheistic world is one where the actions of all particles of matter have been predetermined thru cause and effect, and thus free will is illusory.  Heck, IBM has already created a quantum computer that is based on the &quot;wacky&quot; concept that subatomic particles can spin in different directions at the same time:  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.cnn.com/2000/TECH/computing/08/15/quantum.reut/index.html">www.cnn.com/2000/TECH/com...index.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
When particles can exhibit multiple states of behavior at the same time, what does this say about the universe in general?  Does this mean that our actions and behavior are not necessarily written in stone even in an atheistic universe?  I don't have the answer, I just thought this was a fun question. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ukerai.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kerai</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Necrobish</span><br>  Posts: 1464<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/26/02 1:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=364>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: bleh</span><hr size=1> think you got athiesm in the wrong sense there. Athiesm is not the belief that everything is pre-determined, but that there is no God. <p><center>
